The session will empower and enable participants to recognise that they have a unique perspective on the world, and that thoughts from that perspective are worth capturing and sharing.

Abstract (100 words)

A picture says a thousand words - and it’s never been easier to create and share images that can have real impact.

If you’d asked me a couple of years ago - “Can you draw?” I’d have said “Not really - I’m a programmer”. However, creating visual thoughts is now central to everything I do.

This session will illustrate how a visual thought can be captured, created and shared. Before the session, we'll have gathered up some quotes from earlier keynotes, with participants choosing one that resonates to turn into a visual articulation. I'll share techniques and tricks relating to how I go about visually articulating a thought that resonates with me.

Visual thoughts are limited by the ability to listen and understand, and not by a lack of artistic talent…

Please provide a longer description with any and all information you would like us to know about your session, the topic, and what it will entail. (300 word max)

I’ll unpack the process I go through: Listen - Capture - Visualise - Create - Edit - Share and briefly share the devices and apps that I use to help me.

However, the main thrust of the session is to get people past the "I can't draw for toffee" barrier, and see what happens when they have a go. Encouragement plays a large part, as does a community of people having a go at the same time.

I've ran this session twice before at Mozfest, and it works well with an active audience willing to think for themselves, and have a go at learning something new. It never ceases to amaze me that even though a number of people might focus in on a particular quote, the visual articulations are so different, even though they were in the same environment at the same time to hear the thought being uttered. It's because each of us has a unique perspective when listening to or understanding anything. 

From a commons perspective, this session encourages the self-realisation that each commoner's perspective has a unique value, and that sharing the insights from that perspective enriches the commons.



